  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Direct Object (المفعول به)",
      "titleArabic": "المفعول به",
      "content": [
        "The direct object (المفعول به) is the noun that receives the action of the verb.",
        "It is always in the accusative case (منصوب), shown by fatha or its variants."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "The direct object answers 'what?' or 'whom?' after the verb",
        "It takes accusative case markers: fatha (ـَ), alif (ًا), or ya (ين) for plurals",
        "Word order: Verb + Subject + Object (most common)",
        "Object pronouns attach directly to the verb"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "قَرَأَ الطَّالِبُ الْكِتَابَ", "english": "The student read the book" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُ رَجُلًا", "english": "I saw a man" },
        { "arabic": "سَمِعْتُ الْمُدَرِّسِينَ", "english": "I heard the teachers" },
        { "arabic": "قَرَأْتُهُ", "english": "I read it" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Object Pronouns",
      "titleArabic": "ضمائر المفعول به",
      "content": [
        "Object pronouns attach to the end of the verb to indicate the receiver of the action.",
        "These are the same suffixes used for possession, but with verbs they indicate the object."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "ـهُ - him/it (رَأَيْتُهُ - I saw him)",
        "ـهَا - her/it (رَأَيْتُهَا - I saw her)",
        "ـكَ - you (m.) (رَأَيْتُكَ - I saw you)",
        "ـنِي - me (رَآنِي - he saw me)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهُ فِي السُّوقِ", "english": "I saw him in the market" },
        { "arabic": "سَأَلَتْنِي الْمُدَرِّسَةُ", "english": "The teacher asked me" },
        { "arabic": "سَاعَدْتُهُمْ", "english": "I helped them" },
        { "arabic": "أَعْطَاهَا الْكِتَابَ", "english": "He gave her the book" }
      ]
    }
  ],
